# 五、Band 8 优化版（建议精读）

The charts illustrate the locations of dance classes attended by young people in an Australian town and compare participation in three types of dance classes across two age groups.

Overall, private studios were by far the most common venue for dance classes, whereas college-based studios represented the smallest proportion. In terms of class types, ballet was particularly popular among children under 11, while modern dance attracted the highest number of students aged 11–16.

Regarding the locations of dance classes, almost half of all classes were held in private studios, accounting for 48% of the total. School halls used for after-school programmes were the second most common venue, representing 24%. Community halls and other locations together made up 18%, while only 10% of classes took place in college-based studios.

As for the types of dance classes, ballet was by far the most popular dance style among children under 11, with approximately 600 students, compared with only around 300 students aged 11–16. By contrast, modern dance showed the opposite pattern. Around 520 teenagers attended modern dance classes, whereas the figure for younger children was only about 300. Tap dance attracted broadly similar numbers in both age groups, with roughly 450 students aged under 11 and just over 400 among those aged 11–16.

